In this article, President Obama visits Grand Isle, Louisiana, and speaks with local residents who have been affected by the oil spill. He meets with business owners, such as a marina owner, shrimp boat owner, oyster fisherman, and convenience store owner, who are all facing economic hardships due to the spill. The President discusses the impact the spill has had on their livelihoods and the community as a whole. He emphasizes the need for coordination between the state, federal, and local governments, as well as BP, to minimize the damage and ensure that claims are being processed effectively. The residents express their concerns about the lasting impact of the spill and the need for immediate action. The President assures them that he and Admiral Allen are committed to helping them and holding those responsible accountable. The article highlights the resilience of the community and their support for one another during this difficult time.